I’m not sure this question is best suited for the bug tracker, but since I wasn’t able to get an answer [on StackOverflow](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/36795202/vscode-extension-language-inlining-with-es6-template-strings), I’m taking my chance here. Sorry if this isn’t the right place.

So my question is about how extensions could provide language support (autocompletion, linter, syntax highlighting, snippets, etc.) for tagged ES6 template strings? My particular use case is about GraphQL queries that are very likely to be defined in JavaScript/Typescript files like in the below [Facebook/Relay](https://facebook.github.io/relay/) example:

``` es6
Tea = Relay.createContainer(Tea, {
  fragments: {
    tea: () => Relay.QL`
      fragment on Tea {
        name,
        steepingTime,
      }
    `,
  },
});
```

Here I would like [my GraphQL extension](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=mquandalle.graphql) to support its features inside of the tagged `Relay.QL` string. Is there any way to do that currently?

- VSCode Version: 1.00
- OS Version: Win 10

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Install node.js 6.0.0
2. Try to debug within a router.get function.

```
router.get("/:id", (req, res, next) => {
    controller.getSingle(req.params.id).then(data => res.json(data));
});
```

When I add a breakpoint at the `controller.` call, the debugger stops when I'm using node 5.11.0. It does not after upgrading to 6.0.0. The debugger stops (so it notices a breakpoint), but it doesn't show the line where it stopped anywhere.

Breakpoints outside of the express calls work fine by the way. So when I add a breakpoint at the router.get, it works (but at the start of the application, which is good, obviously).

Changing from () => to function() did not change anything.
